        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/b487fb/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2022-03-04T06:31:48.934Z",
        "cooked": "<p>They might have to also consider using a different audio codec or changing its parameters when computer audio shared, as the current one is optimized for human voice and will degrade the sound quality of music, gameplay, and other non-human sounds as it tries to noise cancel. Also has to not include Signal sounds so that other people in the call donâ€™t echo.</p>\n<p>Optimally, they would allow both mic input and sharing of computer audio simultaneously.</p>\n<p>For music, changes would have to be made for all clients: <a href=\"https://github.com/signalapp/ringrtc/issues/24\" class=\"inline-onebox\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">Opus audio quality poor for music Â· Issue #24 Â· signalapp/ringrtc Â· GitHub</a></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>if you are experimenting, you could try to modify this line <a href=\"https://github.com/signalapp/ringrtc-private/blob/830779be6e7297713d2ff8ae49ff41f5ca4e20e1/src/rust/src/core/bandwidth_mode.rs#L84\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://github.com/signalapp/ringrtc-private/blob/830779be6e7297713d2ff8ae49ff41f5ca4e20e1/src/rust/src/core/bandwidth_mode.rs#L84</a> and set a value of 128_000 for all bitrates (as per the opus rfc).</p>\n<p>You would need to do this on all clients you want to test with since these bitrates are not negotiated. This might help. However, the current design of audio for Signal clients is focused on speech and you may run in to other issues such as stereo (most of it expects a mono input signal) and jitter settings (if you wanted to stream music, a slightly longer buffer would be helpful to eliminate choppy sounds in bad network conditions).</p>\n</blockquote>",
